<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-12-08T09:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-12-08T09:36:00-05:00" n="894" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d894">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">818.00/944: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at San José</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Chase</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">San
                                            José</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-12-08T09:00:00-05:36"><hi rend="italic">December
                                            8, 1919, 9 a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received December 9, 12.50 p.m.</hi>]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>My December 4, 11 a.m.<note n="32" xml:id="d894fn32">Not
                                    printed.</note> Julio Acosta elected President of the Republic
                                yesterday by a very great majority. Good order maintained. Saloons
                                closed. Election well conducted. Opposition may have a few deputies
                                owing to proportional method of electing. Particulars by mail.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Chase</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>